â€¢ Definition: CI/CD is a core concept of DevOps that automates the process of moving code from development to production.
â€¢ The Problem: In large applications (like E-commerce), multiple developers work on the same codebase. Manually merging, testing, and deploying code leads to "Integration Hell," errors, and slow releases.


ğŸ—ï¸ 2. The Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC) Steps
Any change (bug fix or new feature) goes through these stages:

1. Develop
   Writing code on a local branch.

2. Commit/Push
   Merging local changes into the main branch (often using Git).

3. Build
   Creating Deployable Artifacts (Build Files).
   â€¢ Includes source code + dependencies + libraries.
   â€¢ Examples: Binary files, Executable files, or .apk files for Android.

4. Test
   Running various automated tests.

5. Release
   Making the application available to end-users.

6. Deploy
   Making the code available on a specific environment.


ğŸ§ª 3. Types of Testing in CI/CD

Testing is divided into two phases:

Pre-Deployment Tests:
â€¢ Unit Tests â€“ Testing individual components (usually done by developers).
â€¢ Integration Tests â€“ Checking if different components work together correctly.
â€¢ Regression Tests â€“ Ensuring new changes haven't broken existing functionality.

Post-Deployment (End-to-End / E2E Tests):
â€¢ Performed after deploying to Staging or Production.
â€¢ Includes Security Tests, Smoke Tests, Alpha/Beta Testing.


ğŸŒ 4. Deployment Environments

Organizations typically maintain three main environments:

1. Dev (Development)
   Used only by developers for internal testing.

2. Staging (Pre-Production)
   A replica of production used for final demos, manager/CTO approvals, and E2E testing.

3. Prod (Production)
   The live environment accessed by real end-users.


ğŸ”„ 5. CI vs. CD (The Two Types of CD)

CI: Continuous Integration
â€¢ Automates the Build and Test steps.
â€¢ Triggered every time a developer commits code.

CD: Continuous Delivery vs Continuous Deployment

Feature: Automation
â€¢ Continuous Delivery: Automates up to Staging
â€¢ Continuous Deployment: Fully automated up to Production

Feature: Approval
â€¢ Continuous Delivery: Manual approval required
â€¢ Continuous Deployment: No manual intervention

Feature: Use Case
â€¢ Continuous Delivery: Banking, Fintech
â€¢ Continuous Deployment: Netflix, Hotstar


âš–ï¸ 6. Why do we need CI/CD? (Manual vs Automated)

Manual Issues:
â€¢ Integration Hell â€“ Hard to merge multiple developersâ€™ code.
â€¢ Code Freeze â€“ Stopping work to manually test and deploy.
â€¢ Error Prone â€“ Humans miss bugs in repetitive tasks.
â€¢ Backup Restore â€“ Slow recovery causes downtime.

CI/CD Benefits:
â€¢ Speed & Reliability â€“ Small, frequent, tested releases.
â€¢ Zero Downtime â€“ Users donâ€™t face crashes during updates.
â€¢ Automation â€“ YAML scripts handle repetitive work.


